    brief:'A mother brings 3-year-old Mabel, a "picky eater" who refuses most foods and eats a narrow range, with mealtime battles; the child is otherwise WELL and THRIVING (normal growth/energy/development). The task is to manage PICKY/FUSSY EATING (very common, usually a normal phase in toddlers/pre-schoolers): take a history and \u2014 importantly \u2014 confirm the child is GROWING/THRIVING (plot growth) and EXCLUDE red flags/organic causes (faltering growth/weight loss, very restricted intake with deficiency, dysphagia/choking/vomiting, GI symptoms, developmental concerns/autism, food allergy/coeliac, signs of a feeding disorder like ARFID); REASSURE that picky eating is common and usually self-limiting and that growth is the key reassurance; give practical FEEDING/behaviour advice (regular family mealtimes, role-modelling, repeated low-pressure exposure to new foods \u2014 it can take many tries, avoid pressure/force/bribery/battles, manage portion expectations, limit grazing/milk/juice between meals, keep mealtimes positive and short); address the PARENTAL ANXIETY and the battles; and safety-net/refer (dietitian/health visitor/paediatrics) if faltering growth, very restricted range with nutritional concern, or red flags. The skill is red-flag/growth exclusion, reassurance, practical feeding advice, and parental support \u2014 not unnecessary investigation or supplements. No NG12 cancer link.',
