    brief:'Mr Sanjay Mehta, 38, has persistent HALITOSIS (bad breath) affecting his confidence, not fixed by mouthwash. The task is the structured approach to halitosis: recognise that the VAST MAJORITY (~80\u201390%) of halitosis is ORAL in origin (poor oral hygiene, tongue coating, gingivitis/periodontal disease, dental caries/abscess, dry mouth) \u2014 so the first step is ORAL/DENTAL assessment and DENTAL REVIEW; take a history (true vs perceived/halitophobia, timing, related symptoms), and consider NON-ORAL causes where appropriate: ENT (chronic sinusitis/post-nasal drip, tonsil stones/tonsillitis), GI (GORD \u2014 though "stomach causes" are over-attributed; the classic GORD link and the question stem\u2019s GORD), respiratory infections, systemic/metabolic (diabetic ketoacidosis \u2014 ketotic breath, hepatic/renal failure \u2014 distinctive odours, which are red flags), drugs, smoking and diet; MANAGE with oral hygiene optimisation (brushing, interdental cleaning, TONGUE cleaning, treating gum disease, hydration, smoking/diet), dental referral, and treat any identified cause (e.g. GORD, sinusitis); and address the psychological/social impact and reassure (recognise halitophobia where breath is objectively normal). The skill is the oral-first structured approach, dental referral, considering systemic red flags, and treating the cause. No NG12 cancer link (though persistent oral/throat lesions/symptoms would prompt head-and-neck cancer thought).',
