    learning:'RESTLESS LEGS SYNDROME (RLS) is recognised by four core features: an URGE to move the legs (often with an unpleasant crawling/uncomfortable sensation), worse at REST, relieved by MOVEMENT, and worse in the EVENING/at night. It commonly first occurs or worsens in PREGNANCY (especially the third trimester) and usually resolves after delivery. The key, easily-missed step is to check for and treat IRON DEFICIENCY, a common treatable secondary cause/contributor particularly relevant in pregnancy \u2014 check ferritin (and FBC), as low or even low-normal iron stores contribute and iron replacement often improves RLS. Screen other contributors (thyroid and renal function; medications that can worsen RLS \u2014 some antidepressants such as SSRIs/mirtazapine, antihistamines, dopamine-antagonist antiemetics; caffeine) and address modifiable ones. Manage conservatively first \u2014 especially important in pregnancy \u2014 with sleep hygiene, gentle exercise/stretching/walking, leg massage, warmth/heat, reducing caffeine and evening triggers, and treating iron deficiency, because most standard dopaminergic RLS medications are avoided or used with caution in pregnancy and should not be reached for routinely. Reassure that pregnancy-related RLS is common and usually resolves after delivery and that conservative measures plus iron are the mainstay, and for severe/refractory symptoms seek obstetric/neurology specialist advice on safe options rather than prescribing standard RLS drugs unsafely. The skill is recognising RLS, checking/treating iron deficiency, conservative pregnancy-safe management, reassurance about post-delivery resolution, and caution with medication. No NICE NG12 cancer pathway applies.',
